Find the longest string in a list using reduce().

Input:
List<String> data = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "pear", "watermelon");

Solutions:-

Java 8 reduce finds longest string by iteratively comparing lengths. For input ["apple", "banana", "pear", "watermelon"], returns "watermelon" (10 chars).

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream strings via stream(). reduce with binary operator (s1, s2) -> s1.length() > s2.length() ? s1 : s2 picks longer each step. Returns Optional<String>.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class LongestStringReduce {
    public static void findLongest(List<String> data) {
        data.stream()
            .reduce((s1, s2) -> s1.length() > s2.length() ? s1 : s2)
            .ifPresent(System.out::println);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> data = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "pear", "watermelon");
        findLongest(data);
    }
}

Prints watermelon. Ties keep first.
â€‹

#Thought Process
reduce folds stream with accumulator; comparator lambda selects max length. No identity needed (2-arg). ifPresent handles empty. Efficient O(n), single pass.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty: Empty Optional, no print.
Single: Returns it.
Tie lengths: First wins.
Null list: NPE.
Null strings: NPE on length.
